@node FAQ
@{b}Q: How do I define a horizontal line?@{ub}

A: Try this:
   \\table 1
   70
   l
   This creates a horizontal line with a length of 70 characters.
   

@{b}Q: How do I disable the horizontal (vertical) lines of a table?@{ub}

A: Try this:
   \\set-hline
   \\set-vline


@{b}Q: I want to set the vertical line character of a table to **.@{ub}

A: Try this:
   \\set-vline **


@{b}Q: I want to use different horizontal lines within a table.@{ub}

A: Set a character for the horizontal line before issuing a table tag.

     Tag     Line position
     ---------------------
     \\table  above
     \\header below
     \\row    below


@{b}Q: asc2frm does not recognize my tags.@{ub}

A: Some tags must be at the beginning of the current line.


@{b}Q: The word "tem" and the remainder of the document are printed in
   italics.@{ub}

A: The line contains an error: "item outside list".


@{b}Q: I want to use different cell formats in the table rows.@{ub}

A: Insert a \\table tag before each \\header or \\row tag.
@endnode

@node em "Error messages"
asc2frm generates an error message containing the current line number
when it encounters a problem.

asc2frm generates the following error messages:

  Error message             Solution
  --------------------------------------------------------------
  broken table format       Specify one character for each row
                            to create.
  item outside list (1)     Wrap a list environment around the
                            line(s) using \\[o]list and \\endlist.
  header outside table      Wrap a table environment around the
                            line(s) using \\table and \\endtable.
  invalid table format (2)  Use correct format characters (see
                            \\table tag).
  row outside table         Wrap a table environment around the
                            line(s) using \\table and \\endtable.

(1) The following lines are printed in italics, because asc2frm processes
    the \\i of the \\item tag.

(2) This is a "fatal error". The program terminates immediately.
@endnode

@node Installation
Perform one of the following steps:

  (1) Copy "asc2frm" to C:
  
  (2) add its program directory to your PATH

The program needs no additional libraries.


@{b}Compiling the demonstration script "Demo"@{ub}

Just type:

make-demo

This script calls asc2frm in order to create the demonstration output.
@endnode

@node Introduction
@{b}What is asc2frm?@{ub}

"asc2frm" is a text formatting package which uses a simple programming
language to define the layout of a document.

Duplicate blanks and duplicate blank lines are ignored. A special command is
used to define an indentation of a section of text.


@{b}Features@{ub}

o  sections
o  (numbered) titles and subtitles
o  numbered and bullet lists
o  bold, italic, underlined, and reverse text
o  4 foreground and background colours
o  indentations
o  tables

Lists can be nested to a maximum of 1,024 levels. Up to 1,024 sections can be
definded. Tables may consist of up tp 1,024 columns.


@{b}Output formats@{ub}

The output files may be in ASCII, ANSI (for printing to PRT: or displaying
with MORE), or AmigaGuide format. By default, an index is created for Amiga-
Guide documents.


@{b}Purpose@{ub}

"asc2frm" is of use if you want to have the same information in several
document formats.

Any change has only to be made once. After that, you can compile the source
file to any output format you want.

Without "asc2frm", you had to change each file by yourself. Probably, one
would forget to change something in that case, or insert a lot of errors,
etc.
@endnode

@node Commands
@{b}Misc tags@{ub}

  Tag        Result
  --------------------
  \\          \\
  \~          one blank
  \\new-line  line feed
  
If the output format is -[plain]guide, \\ is expanded to \\\\.

The \~ tag is used to insert several spaces (which are ignored otherwise).


@{b}Character formatting@{ub}

  Tag  Result
  -----------------------------------------
  \\b   Turn bold on
  \\i   Turn italics on
  \\r   Turn reverse on
  \\u   Turn underline on
  \\n   Turn \\b, \\i, \\r, \\u off
  
  \\0   Set foreground colour to 0 ("back")
  \\1   Set foreground colour to 1 ("text")
  \\2   Set foreground colour to 2 ("shine")
  \\3   Set foreground colour to 3 ("fill")
  
  \\4   Set background colour to 0 ("back")
  \\5   Set background colour to 1 ("text")
  \\6   Set background colour to 2 ("shine")
  \\7   Set background colour to 3 ("fill")
  
  \\^   Turn superscript on
  \\_   Turn subscript on
  \\-   Turn \\^, \\_ off

Note: \\^ and \\_ are not supported by all output devices.


@{b}Lists@{ub}

  Tag       Result
  ----------------------------------
  \\list     Start bullet list
  \\olist    Start numbered list
  \\item     Insert an item
  \\endlist  Leave current list level

Items may consist of several lines of text. Lists may be nested up to a
level of 1,024.

The last list level is continued when the current one is left.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{i}Example: Create a bulleted list with 2 items @{ui}

\\list
\\item First item
\\item Second item
\\endlist
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  
@{b}Headers@{ub}

  Tag           Result
  -------------------------------------------------
  \\title x      Print header x (bold)
  \\ntitle x     Print number and header x (bold)
  \\subtitle x   Print header x (italics)
  \\nsubtitle x  Print number and header x (italics)

A header must not contain any tags.


@{b}Sections@{ub}

  Tag         Result
  -----------------------------------------
  \\section x  Starts a new section called x
  
Sections are AmigaGuide nodes. The \\section tag is ignored if another
output format than -[plain]guide is selected. Up to 1,024 sections may be
created.

A section header must not contain any tags.


@{b}The VERBATIM environment@{ub}

The VERBATIM environment disables all tags. Duplicate spaces and duplicate
blank lines are printed to the output file.

  Tag           Result
  ----------------------------------------
  \\verbatim     Starts VERBATIM environment
  \\endverbatim  Leaves VERBATIM environment
  

@{b}Tables@{ub}

Note: Table tags must not contain any other tags.

The characters used for vertical or horizontal lines respectively may
be changed using the \\set-vline and \\set-hline tags.

The number of columns is limited to 1,024 per table.

The number of rows is unlimited.

  Tag        Result
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  \\table x   Starts a table definition. x is the number of columns
             to be created and must not exceed 1,024.
             - the next x lines of text must contain the lengths of
               all columns in characters
             - the last (x+1) line must contain a format string
               which contains 'l', 'r', or 'c' for each column (left,
               right, or centered)
             This tags creates a horizontal line if a new table is created.
  \\endtable  Leaves the table environment. @{b}No line feed is inserted.@{ub}
             @{i}This tag is optional. If it is omitted, you may continue
             the current table after writing some lines of normal
             text - just add another \\row or \\header tag.@{ui}
  \\header    Creates a table header which is set in bold face.
             - each column starts with a vertical line
             - each column is formatted according to the format string
             - the header ends with a vertical line
  \\row       Creates a table row.
             - each column starts with a vertical line
             - each column is formatted according to the format string
             - the row ends with a vertical line

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{i}Example: Create a simple invoice @{ui}

\\table 4
20
10
10
10
lrrr
\\header
Item
Price
Amount
Total
\\row
Disks
2.00
5
10.00
\\row
Printer
100.00
1
100.00
\\endtable
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@endnode

@node Options
All options are set using \\set-??? tags.

  Tag            Result
  ----------------------------------------------------------------
  \\set-bullet x  The bullet character is set to x (defaults to ·)
  \\set-count     Headers without numbers are counted
  \\set-hline x   The character used for horizontal lines in tables
                 is set to x (defaults to -). The character may be
                 omitted in order to disable horizontal lines.
  \\set-indent x  The left margin is set to x
  \\set-item x    The next item # is set to x
  \\set-nocount   Headers without numbers are not counted
  \\set-title x   The next header # will be x
  \\set-vline x   The character(s) used for vertical lines in tables
                 is (are) set to x (defaults to |). The character
                 may be omitted in order to disable vertical lines.
  
@endnode

@node Usage
Usage: asc2frm [-ascii|-ansi|-[plain]guide] file

asc2frm is a simple text formatter. It reads <file> and converts it
to the desired output format.

If no format is specified, '-ansi' is used.


@{b}Output formats@{ub}

  Format       Extension  Result
  --------------------------------------------------------------
  -ascii       .asc       Plain ASCII file
  -ansi        .prt       ANSI file
  -guide       .guide     AmigaGuide document with index node
  -plainguide  .guide     AmigaGuide document without index node
  
ANSI files can be displayed with MORE. Use PRT: as device if you want to
print such a file.

The output file gets the name of the input file plus the extension stated
above.


@{b}Log files@{ub}

asc2frm creates a log file (*.err) for each output file it creates.

Each error is printed to the screen.

The log files contain the errors which occured during the compilation of
the source script.

"Fatal errors" are also logged to the output file. They cause asc2frm to
terminate immediately.
@endnode

